Your Turn 1

set.seed(2343)

my_df <- tibble(
  X1 = rnorm(n = 50, mean = rep(c(1, 3), each = 25)),
  X2 = rnorm(n = 50, mean = rep(c(1.3, 1), each = 25))
)

my_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(X1, X2)) +
  geom_point() + theme_tufte()

  1. How many clusters can you identify in the data?

Answer:

  1. Fit kmeans algorithm to the data picking the number of clusters you previously identified in part a.
set.seed(1234)
res_kmeans <- kmeans(my_df, centers = 2, nstart = 25)
augment(res_kmeans, data = my_df) %>%
  ggplot(aes(X1, X2, color = .cluster)) +
  geom_point()

  1. Repeat parts b-c for identifying 3 clusters instead of 2.
set.seed(1234)
res_kmeans <- kmeans(my_df, centers = 3, nstart = 25)
augment(res_kmeans, data = my_df) %>%
  ggplot(aes(X1, X2, color = .cluster)) +
  geom_point()

multi_kmeans <- tibble(k = 1:10) %>%
  mutate(
    model = purrr::map(k, ~ kmeans(my_df, centers = .x, nstart = 25)),
    tot.withinss = purrr::map_dbl(model, ~ glance(.x)$tot.withinss)
  )
multi_kmeans %>%
  ggplot(aes(k, tot.withinss)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:15) +
  theme_minimal()

set.seed(1234)
kmeans.final <- kmeans(my_df, 5, nstart = 25)
fviz_cluster(kmeans.final, data = my_df)

  1. Find the euclidean distance between X1 and X2 in the dataset my_df. This will be stored in a matrix with each entries denoting the euclidean distance between the corresponding states.

  1. Set-up the hierarchical clustering object that we will use to construct a dendogram
hc1 <- hclust(d)
  1. Cut the tree in two groups
sub_grp <- cutree(hc1, k = 3)
  1. Make a data tibble adding the cluster information to a new column called cluster.
my_df %>% 
  mutate(cluster = sub_grp) %>%
  head
  1. Finally, plot the dendogram
plot(hc1, cex = 0.6)
rect.hclust(hc1, k = 3, border = 2:5)   # Number of clusters
